# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: cocos2d
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:cocos2d/2d-computer-graphics] 2D computer graphics are mainly used in applications that were originally developed upon traditional printing and drawing technologies, such as typography, cartography, technical drawing, advertising, etc.
[src:cocos2d/2d-computer-graphics] In many domains, such as desktop publishing, engineering, and business, a description of a document based on 2D computer graphics techniques can be much smaller than the corresponding digital image—often by a factor of 1/1000 or more.
[src:cocos2d/2d-computer-graphics] This representation is also more flexible since it can be rendered at different resolutions to suit different output devices.
[src:cocos2d/2d-computer-graphics] For these reasons, documents and illustrations are often stored or transmitted as 2D graphic files.
[src:cocos2d/2d-computer-graphics] 2D computer graphics started in the 1950s, based on vector graphics devices.
[src:cocos2d/2d-computer-graphics] These were largely supplanted by raster-based devices in the following decades.
[src:cocos2d/2d-computer-graphics] The PostScript language and the X Window System protocol were landmark developments in the field.
[src:cocos2d/2d-computer-graphics] 2D graphics models may combine geometric models (also called vector graphics), digital images (also called raster graphics), text to be typeset (defined by content, font style and size, color, position, and orientation), mathematical functions and equations, and more.
[src:cocos2d/2d-computer-graphics] These components can be modified and manipulated by two-dimensional geometric transformations such as translation, rotation, and scaling.
[src:cocos2d/2d-computer-graphics] In object-oriented graphics, the image is described indirectly by an object endowed with a self-rendering method—a procedure that assigns colors to the image pixels by an arbitrary algorithm.
[src:cocos2d/2d-computer-graphics] Complex models can be built by combining simpler objects, in the paradigms of object-oriented programming.
[src:cocos2d/2d-computer-graphics] In Euclidean geometry, a *translation (geometry)* moves every point a constant distance in a specified direction.
[src:cocos2d/2d-computer-graphics] A translation can be described as a rigid motion: other rigid motions include rotations and reflections.
[src:cocos2d/2d-computer-graphics] A translation can also be interpreted as the addition of a constant vector to every point, or as shifting the origin of the coordinate system.
[src:cocos2d/2d-computer-graphics] If *T* is a translation, then the image of a subset *A* under the function *T* is the **translation** of *A* by *T*.
[src:cocos2d/2d-computer-graphics] The translation of *A* by *T***v** is often written *A* + **v**.
[src:cocos2d/2d-computer-graphics] In a Euclidean space, any translation is an isometry.
[src:cocos2d/2d-computer-graphics] The set of all translations forms the translation group *T*, which is isomorphic to the space itself, and a normal subgroup of Euclidean group *E*(*n* ).
[src:cocos2d/2d-computer-graphics] Since a translation is an affine transformation but not a linear transformation, homogeneous coordinates are normally used to represent the translation operator by a matrix and thus to make it linear.
[src:cocos2d/2d-computer-graphics] Because addition of vectors is commutative, multiplication of translation matrices is therefore also commutative (unlike multiplication of arbitrary matrices).
[src:cocos2d/2d-computer-graphics] In linear algebra, a *rotation matrix* is a matrix that is used to perform a rotation in Euclidean space.
[src:cocos2d/2d-computer-graphics] rotates points in the *xy*-Cartesian plane counterclockwise through an angle *θ* about the origin of the Cartesian coordinate system.
[src:cocos2d/2d-computer-graphics] To perform the rotation using a rotation matrix *R*, the position of each point must be represented by a column vector **v**, containing the coordinates of the point.
[src:cocos2d/2d-computer-graphics] A rotated vector is obtained by using the matrix multiplication *R***v**.
[src:cocos2d/2d-computer-graphics] Since matrix multiplication has no effect on the zero vector (i.e., on the coordinates of the origin), rotation matrices can only be used to describe rotations about the origin of the coordinate system.
[src:cocos2d/2d-computer-graphics] Rotation matrices provide a simple algebraic description of such rotations, and are used extensively for computations in geometry, physics, and computer graphics.
[src:cocos2d/2d-computer-graphics] In 2-dimensional space, a rotation can be simply described by an angle *θ* of rotation, but it can be also represented by the 4 entries of a rotation matrix with 2 rows and 2 columns.
[src:cocos2d/2d-computer-graphics] In 3-dimensional space, every rotation can be interpreted as a rotation by a given angle about a single fixed axis of rotation (see Euler's rotation theorem), and hence it can be simply described by an angle and a vector with 3 entries.
[src:cocos2d/2d-computer-graphics] However, it can also be represented by the 9 entries of a rotation matrix with 3 rows and 3 columns.
[src:cocos2d/2d-computer-graphics] The notion of rotation is not commonly used in dimensions higher than 3; there is a notion of a *rotational displacement*, which can be represented by a matrix, but no associated single axis or angle.
[src:cocos2d/2d-computer-graphics] Rotation matrices are square matrices, with real entries.
[src:cocos2d/2d-computer-graphics] The set of all such matrices of size *n* forms a group, known as the special orthogonal group SO(*n*).
[src:cocos2d/2d-computer-graphics] A convenient way to create a complex image is to start with a blank "canvas" raster map (an array of pixels, also known as a bitmap) filled with some uniform background color and then "draw", "paint" or "paste" simple patches of color onto it, in an appropriate order.
[src:cocos2d/2d-computer-graphics] In particular the canvas may be the frame buffer for a computer display.
[src:cocos2d/2d-computer-graphics] Text, shapes and lines are rendered with a client-specified color.
[src:cocos2d/2d-computer-graphics] Many libraries and cards provide color gradients, which are handy for the generation of smoothly-varying backgrounds, shadow effects, etc.
[src:cocos2d/2d-computer-graphics] The pixel colors can also be taken from a texture, e.g. a digital image (thus emulating rub-on screentones and the fabled *checker paint* which used to be available only in cartoons).
[src:cocos2d/2d-computer-graphics] Painting a pixel with a given color usually replaces its previous color.
[src:cocos2d/2d-computer-graphics] However, many systems support painting with transparent and translucent colors, which only modify the previous pixel values.
[src:cocos2d/2d-computer-graphics] The two colors may also be combined in more complex ways, e.g. by computing their bitwise exclusive or.
[src:cocos2d/2d-computer-graphics] This technique is known as *inverting color* or *color inversion*, and is often used in graphical user interfaces for highlighting, rubber-band drawing, and other volatile painting—since re-painting the same shapes with the same color will restore the original pixel values.
[src:cocos2d/2d-computer-graphics] The models used in 2D computer graphics usually do not provide for three-dimensional shapes, or three-dimensional optical phenomena such as lighting, shadows, reflection, refraction, etc.
[src:cocos2d/2d-computer-graphics] However, they usually can model multiple *layers* (conceptually of ink, paper, or film; opaque, translucent, or transparent—stacked in a specific order.
[src:cocos2d/2d-computer-graphics] The ordering is usually defined by a single number (the layer's *depth*, or distance from the viewer).
[src:cocos2d/2d-computer-graphics] Layered models are sometimes called "21⁄2-D computer graphics".
[src:cocos2d/2d-computer-graphics] They make it possible to mimic traditional drafting and printing techniques based on film and paper, such as cutting and pasting; and allow the user to edit any layer without affecting the others.
[src:cocos2d/2d-computer-graphics] For these reasons, they are used in most graphics editors.
[src:cocos2d/2d-computer-graphics] Layered models also allow better spatial anti-aliasing of complex drawings and provide a sound model for certain techniques such as *mitered joints* and the even–odd rule.
[src:cocos2d/2d-computer-graphics] Layered models are also used to allow the user to suppress unwanted information when viewing or printing a document, e.g. roads or railways from a map, certain process layers from an integrated circuit diagram, or hand annotations from a business letter.
[src:cocos2d/2d-computer-graphics] In a layer-based model, the target image is produced by "painting" or "pasting" each layer, in order of decreasing depth, on the virtual canvas.
[src:cocos2d/2d-computer-graphics] Conceptually, each layer is first rendered on its own, yielding a digital image with the desired resolution which is then painted over the canvas, pixel by pixel.
[src:cocos2d/2d-computer-graphics] Fully transparent parts of a layer need not be rendered, of course.
[src:cocos2d/2d-computer-graphics] The rendering and painting may be done in parallel, i.e., each layer pixel may be painted on the canvas as soon as it is produced by the rendering procedure.
[src:cocos2d/2d-computer-graphics] Layers that consist of complex geometric objects (such as text or polylines) may be broken down into simpler elements (characters or line segments, respectively), which are then painted as separate layers, in some order.
[src:cocos2d/2d-computer-graphics] However, this solution may create undesirable aliasing artifacts wherever two elements overlap the same pixel.
[src:cocos2d/2d-computer-graphics] See also Portable Document Format#Layers.
[src:cocos2d/2d-computer-graphics] Modern computer graphics card displays almost overwhelmingly use raster techniques, dividing the screen into a rectangular grid of pixels, due to the relatively low cost of raster-based video hardware as compared with vector graphic hardware.
[src:cocos2d/2d-computer-graphics] Most graphic hardware has internal support for blitting operations or sprite drawing.
[src:cocos2d/2d-computer-graphics] A co-processor dedicated to blitting is known as a *Blitter chip*.
[src:cocos2d/2d-computer-graphics] Many graphical user interfaces (GUIs), including macOS, Microsoft Windows, or the X Window System, are primarily based on 2D graphical concepts.
[src:cocos2d/2d-computer-graphics] Such software provides a visual environment for interacting with the computer, and commonly includes some form of window manager to aid the user in conceptually distinguishing between different applications.
[src:cocos2d/2d-computer-graphics] The user interface within individual software applications is typically 2D in nature as well, due in part to the fact that most common input devices, such as the mouse, are constrained to two dimensions of movement.
[src:cocos2d/2d-computer-graphics] 2D graphics are very important in the control peripherals such as printers, plotters, sheet cutting machines, etc.
[src:cocos2d/2d-computer-graphics] They were also used in most early video games; and are still used for card and board games such as solitaire, chess, mahjongg, etc.
[src:cocos2d/2d-computer-graphics] 2D graphics editors or *drawing programs* are application-level software for the creation of images, diagrams and illustrations by direct manipulation (through the mouse, graphics tablet, or similar device) of 2D computer graphics primitives.
[src:cocos2d/2d-computer-graphics] These editors generally provide geometric primitives as well as digital images; and some even support procedural models.
[src:cocos2d/2d-computer-graphics] The illustration is usually represented internally as a layered model, often with a hierarchical structure to make editing more convenient.
[src:cocos2d/2d-computer-graphics] These editors generally output graphics files where the layers and primitives are separately preserved in their original form.
[src:cocos2d/2d-computer-graphics] MacDraw, introduced in 1984 with the Macintosh line of computers, was an early example of this class; recent examples are the commercial products Adobe Illustrator and CorelDRAW, and the free editors such as xfig or Inkscape.
[src:cocos2d/2d-computer-graphics] There are also many 2D graphics editors specialized for certain types of drawings such as electrical, electronic and VLSI diagrams, topographic maps, computer fonts, etc.
[src:cocos2d/2d-computer-graphics] Image editors are specialized for the manipulation of digital images, mainly by means of free-hand drawing/painting and signal processing operations.
[src:cocos2d/2d-computer-graphics] They typically use a direct-painting paradigm, where the user controls virtual pens, brushes, and other free-hand artistic instruments to apply paint to a virtual canvas.
[src:cocos2d/2d-computer-graphics] Some image editors support a multiple-layer model; however, in order to support signal-processing operations like blurring each layer is normally represented as a digital image.
[src:cocos2d/2d-computer-graphics] Therefore, any geometric primitives that are provided by the editor are immediately converted to pixels and painted onto the canvas.
[src:cocos2d/2d-computer-graphics] The name *raster graphics editor* is sometimes used to contrast this approach to that of general editors which also handle *vector graphics*.
[src:cocos2d/2d-computer-graphics] One of the first popular image editors was Apple's MacPaint, companion to MacDraw.
[src:cocos2d/2d-computer-graphics] Modern examples are the free GIMP editor, and the commercial products Photoshop and Paint Shop Pro.
[src:cocos2d/2d-computer-graphics] This class too includes many specialized editors—for medicine, remote sensing, digital photography, etc.
[src:cocos2d/2d-computer-graphics] With the resurgence of 2D animation, free and proprietary software packages have become widely available for amateurs and professional animators.
[src:cocos2d/2d-computer-graphics] With software like RETAS UbiArt Framework and Adobe After Effects, coloring and compositing can be done in less time.
[src:cocos2d/2d-computer-graphics] Various approaches have been developed to aid and speed up the process of digital 2D animation.
[src:cocos2d/2d-computer-graphics] For example, by generating vector artwork in a tool like Adobe Flash an artist may employ software-driven automatic coloring and in-betweening.
[src:cocos2d/2d-computer-graphics] Programs like Blender or Adobe Substance allow the user to do either 3D animation, 2D animation or combine both in its software allowing experimentation with multiple forms of animation.
[src:cocos2d/cocos2d] Cocos2d was first released in 2008, and was originally written in Python.
[src:cocos2d/cocos2d] It contains many branches with the best known being Cocos2d-ObjC (formerly known as Cocos2d-iPhone), Cocos2d-x, Cocos2d-JS and Cocos2d-XNA.
[src:cocos2d/cocos2d] There are also many third-party tools, editors and libraries made by the Cocos2d community, such as particle editors, spritesheet editors, font editors, and level editors, like SpriteBuilder and CocoStudio.
[src:cocos2d/cocos2d] All versions of Cocos2d work using the basic primitive known as a sprite.
[src:cocos2d/cocos2d] A sprite can be thought of as a simple 2D image, but can also be a container for other sprites.
[src:cocos2d/cocos2d] In Cocos2D, sprites are arranged together to form a scene, like a game level or a menu.
[src:cocos2d/cocos2d] Sprites can be manipulated in code based on events or actions or as part of animations.
[src:cocos2d/cocos2d] The sprites can be moved, rotated, scaled, have their image changed, etc.
[src:cocos2d/cocos2d] Cocos2D provides basic animation primitives that can work on sprites using a set of actions and timers.
[src:cocos2d/cocos2d] They can be chained and composed together to form more complex animations.
[src:cocos2d/cocos2d] Most Cocos2D implementations let you manipulate the size, scale, position, and other effects of the sprite.
[src:cocos2d/cocos2d] Some versions of Cocos2D let you also animate particle effects, image filtering effects via shaders (warp, ripple, etc.).
[src:cocos2d/cocos2d] Cocos2D provides primitives to represent common GUI elements in game scenes.
[src:cocos2d/cocos2d] This includes things like text boxes, labels, menus, buttons, and other common elements.
[src:cocos2d/cocos2d] Many Cocos2D implementations come with support for common 2D physics engines like Box2D and Chipmunk.
[src:cocos2d/cocos2d] Various versions of Cocos2D have audio libraries that wrap OpenAL or other libraries to provide full audio capabilities.
[src:cocos2d/cocos2d] Features are dependent on the implementation of Cocos2D.
[src:cocos2d/cocos2d] Support binding to JavaScript, Lua, and other engines exist for Cocos2D.
[src:cocos2d/cocos2d] For example, Cocos2d JavaScript Binding (JSB) for C/C++/Objective-C is the wrapper code that sits between native code and JavaScript code using Mozilla's SpiderMonkey.
[src:cocos2d/cocos2d] With JSB, you can accelerate your development process by writing your game using easy and flexible JavaScript.
[src:cocos2d/cocos2d] February 2008, in the village of Los Cocos, near Córdoba, Argentina, Ricardo Quesada, a game developer, and Lucio Torre created a 2D game engine for Python with several of their developer friends.
[src:cocos2d/cocos2d] They named it "Los Cocos" after its birthplace.
[src:cocos2d/cocos2d] A month later, the group released the version 0.1 and changed its name to "Cocos2d".
[src:cocos2d/cocos2d] Attracted by the potential of the new Apple App Store for the iPhone, Quesada rewrote Cocos2d in Objective-C and in June 2008 released "Cocos2d for iPhone" v0.1, the predecessor of the later Cocos2d family.
[src:cocos2d/cocos2d] Cocos2D-ObjC (formerly known as Cocos2D-iPhone and Cocos2D-SpriteBuilder), is maintained by Lars Birkemose.
[src:cocos2d/cocos2d] Also, the English designer Michael Heald designed a new logo for Cocos2d (the Cocos2d logo was previously a running coconut).
[src:cocos2d/cocos2d] November 2010, a developer from China named Zhe Wang branched Cocos2d-x based on Cocos2d.
[src:cocos2d/cocos2d] Cocos2d-x is also a free engine under MIT License, and it allows for compiling and running on multiple platforms with one code base.
[src:cocos2d/cocos2d] In 2013, Quesada left cocos2d-iPhone and joined in cocos2d-x team.
[src:cocos2d/cocos2d] In March 2017, Quesada was laid off from the Chukong company.
[src:cocos2d/cocos2d] In 2015, there are 4 cocos2d branches being actively maintained.
[src:cocos2d/cocos2d] Cocos2d-x & Cocos2d-html5 is maintained and sponsored by developers at Chukong Technologies.
[src:cocos2d/cocos2d] Chukong is also developing CocoStudio, which is a WYSIWYG editor for Cocos2d-x and Cocos2D-html5, and a free Cocos3d-x fork of the Cocos3D project.
[src:cocos2d/cocos2d] Cocos2d has been ported into various programming languages and to all kinds of platforms.
[src:cocos2d/cross-platform-software] Within computing, **cross-platform software** (also called **multi-platform software**, **platform-agnostic software**, or **platform-independent software**) is computer software that is designed to work in several computing platforms.
[src:cocos2d/cross-platform-software] For example, a cross-platform application may run on Linux, macOS and Microsoft Windows.
[src:cocos2d/cross-platform-software] Cross-platform software may run on many platforms, or as few as two.
[src:cocos2d/cross-platform-software] Some frameworks for cross-platform development are Codename One, ArkUI-X, Kivy, Qt, GTK, Flutter, NativeScript, Xamarin, Apache Cordova, Ionic, and React Native.
[src:cocos2d/cross-platform-software] A hardware platform can refer to an instruction set architecture.
[src:cocos2d/cross-platform-software] For example: ARM or the x86 architecture.
[src:cocos2d/cross-platform-software] These machines can run different operating systems.
[src:cocos2d/cross-platform-software] Smartphones and tablets generally run ARM architecture, these often run Android or iOS and other mobile operating systems.
[src:cocos2d/cross-platform-software] A software platform can be either an operating system (OS) or programming environment, though more commonly it is a combination of both.
[src:cocos2d/cross-platform-software] An exception is Java, which uses an OS-independent virtual machine (VM) to execute Java bytecode.
[src:cocos2d/cross-platform-software] The Java language is typically compiled to run on a VM that is part of the Java platform.
[src:cocos2d/cross-platform-software] The Java virtual machine (Java VM, JVM) is a CPU implemented in software, which runs all Java code.
[src:cocos2d/cross-platform-software] This enables the same code to run on all systems that implement a JVM.
[src:cocos2d/cross-platform-software] Java software can be executed by a hardware-based Java processor.
[src:cocos2d/cross-platform-software] This is used mostly in embedded systems.
[src:cocos2d/cross-platform-software] Java code running in the JVM has access to OS-related services, like disk input/output (I/O) and network access, if the appropriate privileges are granted.
[src:cocos2d/cross-platform-software] The JVM makes the system calls on behalf of the Java application.
[src:cocos2d/cross-platform-software] This lets users to decide the appropriate protection level, depending on an access-control list (ACL).
[src:cocos2d/cross-platform-software] For example, disk and network access is usually enabled for desktop applications, but not for browser-based applets.
[src:cocos2d/cross-platform-software] The Java Native Interface (JNI) can also be used to access OS-specific functions, with a loss of portability.
[src:cocos2d/cross-platform-software] Currently, Java Standard Edition software can run on Microsoft Windows, macOS, several Unix-like OSs, and several real-time operating systems for embedded devices.
[src:cocos2d/cross-platform-software] For mobile applications, browser plugins are used for Windows and Mac based devices, and Android has built-in support for Java.
[src:cocos2d/cross-platform-software] There are also subsets of Java, such as Java Card or Java Platform, Micro Edition, designed for resource-constrained devices.
[src:cocos2d/cross-platform-software] For software to be considered cross-platform, it must function on more than one computer architecture or OS.
[src:cocos2d/cross-platform-software] Developing such software can be a time-consuming task because different OSs have different application programming interfaces (API).
[src:cocos2d/cross-platform-software] Software written for one OS may not automatically work on all architectures that OS supports.
[src:cocos2d/cross-platform-software] Just because software is written in a popular programming language such as C or C++, it does not mean it will run on all OSs that support that language—or even on different versions of the same OS.
[src:cocos2d/cross-platform-software] Web applications are typically described as cross-platform because, ideally, they are accessible from any web browser: the browser is the platform.
[src:cocos2d/cross-platform-software] Web applications generally employ a client–server model, but vary widely in complexity and functionality.
[src:cocos2d/cross-platform-software] It can be hard to reconcile the desire for features with the need for compatibility.
[src:cocos2d/cross-platform-software] Basic web applications perform all or most processing from a stateless server, and pass the result to the client web browser.
[src:cocos2d/cross-platform-software] All user interaction with the application consists of simple exchanges of data requests and server responses.
[src:cocos2d/cross-platform-software] This type of application was the norm in the early phases of World Wide Web application development.
[src:cocos2d/cross-platform-software] Such applications follow a simple transaction model, identical to that of serving static web pages.
[src:cocos2d/cross-platform-software] Today, they are still relatively common, especially where cross-platform compatibility and simplicity are deemed more critical than advanced functionality.
[src:cocos2d/cross-platform-software] Prominent examples of advanced web applications include the Web interface to Gmail and Google Maps.
[src:cocos2d/cross-platform-software] Such applications routinely depend on additional features found only in the more recent versions of popular web browsers.
[src:cocos2d/cross-platform-software] These features include Ajax, JavaScript, Dynamic HTML, SVG, and other components of rich web applications.
[src:cocos2d/cross-platform-software] Because of the competing interests of compatibility and functionality, numerous design strategies have emerged.
[src:cocos2d/cross-platform-software] Many software systems use a layered architecture where platform-dependent code is restricted to the upper- and lowermost layers.
[src:cocos2d/cross-platform-software] Graceful degradation attempts to provide the same or similar functionality to all users and platforms, while diminishing that functionality to a least common denominator for more limited client browsers.
[src:cocos2d/cross-platform-software] For example, a user attempting to use a limited-feature browser to access Gmail may notice that Gmail switches to basic mode, with reduced functionality but still of use.
[src:cocos2d/cross-platform-software] Some software is maintained in distinct codebases for different (hardware and OS) platforms, with equivalent functionality.
[src:cocos2d/cross-platform-software] This requires more effort to maintain the code, but can be worthwhile where the amount of platform-specific code is high.
[src:cocos2d/cross-platform-software] This strategy relies on having one codebase that may be compiled to multiple platform-specific formats.
[src:cocos2d/cross-platform-software] One technique is conditional compilation.
[src:cocos2d/cross-platform-software] With this technique, code that is common to all platforms is not repeated.
[src:cocos2d/cross-platform-software] Blocks of code that are only relevant to certain platforms are made conditional, so that they are only interpreted or compiled when needed.
[src:cocos2d/cross-platform-software] Another technique is separation of functionality, which disables functionality not supported by browsers or OSs, while still delivering a complete application to the user.
[src:cocos2d/cross-platform-software] (See also: Separation of concerns.) This technique is used in web development where interpreted code (as in scripting languages) can query the platform it is running on to execute different blocks conditionally.
[src:cocos2d/cross-platform-software] Third-party libraries attempt to simplify cross-platform capability by hiding the complexities of client differentiation behind a single, unified API, at the expense of vendor lock-in.
[src:cocos2d/cross-platform-software] Responsive web design (RWD) is a Web design approach aimed at crafting the visual layout of sites to provide an optimal viewing experience—easy reading and navigation with a minimum of resizing, panning, and scrolling—across a wide range of devices, from mobile phones to desktop computer monitors.
[src:cocos2d/cross-platform-software] Little or no platform-specific code is used with this technique.
[src:cocos2d/cross-platform-software] Cross-platform applications need much more integration testing.
[src:cocos2d/cross-platform-software] Some web browsers prohibit installation of different versions on the same machine.
[src:cocos2d/cross-platform-software] There are several approaches used to target multiple platforms, but all of them result in software that requires substantial manual effort for testing and maintenance.
[src:cocos2d/cross-platform-software] Techniques such as full virtualization are sometimes used as a workaround for this problem.
[src:cocos2d/cross-platform-software] Tools such as the Page Object Model allow cross-platform tests to be scripted so that one test case covers multiple versions of an app.
[src:cocos2d/cross-platform-software] If different versions have similar user interfaces, all can be tested with one test case.
[src:cocos2d/cross-platform-software] Web applications are becoming increasingly popular but many computer users still use traditional application software which does not rely on a client/web-server architecture.
[src:cocos2d/cross-platform-software] The distinction between traditional and web applications is not always clear.
[src:cocos2d/cross-platform-software] Features, installation methods and architectures for web and traditional applications overlap and blur the distinction.
[src:cocos2d/cross-platform-software] Nevertheless, this simplifying distinction is a common and useful generalization.
[src:cocos2d/cross-platform-software] Traditional application software has been distributed as binary files, especially executable files.
[src:cocos2d/cross-platform-software] Executables only support the platform they were built for—which means that a single cross-platform executable could be very bloated with code that never executes on a particular platform.
[src:cocos2d/cross-platform-software] Instead, generally there is a selection of executables, each built for one platform.
[src:cocos2d/cross-platform-software] For software that is distributed as a binary executable, such as that written in C or C++, there must be a software build for each platform, using a toolset that translates—transcompiles—a single codebase into multiple binary executables.
[src:cocos2d/cross-platform-software] For example, Firefox, an open-source web browser, is available on Windows, macOS (both PowerPC and x86 through what Apple Inc. calls a Universal binary), Linux, and BSD on multiple computer architectures.
[src:cocos2d/cross-platform-software] The four platforms (in this case, Windows, macOS, Linux, and BSD) are separate executable distributions, although they come largely from the same source code.
[src:cocos2d/cross-platform-software] In rare cases, executable code built for several platforms is combined into a single executable file called a fat binary.
[src:cocos2d/cross-platform-software] The use of different toolsets may not be enough to build a working executables for different platforms.
[src:cocos2d/cross-platform-software] In this case, programmers must *port* the source code to the new platform.
[src:cocos2d/cross-platform-software] For example, an application such as Firefox, which already runs on Windows on the x86 family, can be modified and re-built to run on Linux on the x86 (and potentially other architectures) as well.
[src:cocos2d/cross-platform-software] The multiple versions of the code may be stored as separate codebases, or merged into one codebase.
[src:cocos2d/cross-platform-software] An alternative to porting is *cross-platform virtualization*, where applications compiled for one platform can run on another without modification of the source code or binaries.
[src:cocos2d/cross-platform-software] As an example, Apple's Rosetta, which is built into Intel-based Macintosh computers, runs applications compiled for the previous generation of Macs that used PowerPC CPUs.
[src:cocos2d/cross-platform-software] Another example is IBM PowerVM Lx86, which allows Linux/x86 applications to run unmodified on the Linux/Power OS.
[src:cocos2d/cross-platform-software] A script can be considered to be cross-platform if its interpreter is available on multiple platforms and the script only uses the facilities built into the language.
[src:cocos2d/cross-platform-software] For example, a script written in Python for a Unix-like system will likely run with little or no modification on Windows, because Python also runs on Windows; indeed there are many implementations (e.g.
[src:cocos2d/cross-platform-software] The same goes for many of the open-source scripting languages.
[src:cocos2d/cross-platform-software] Unlike binary executable files, the same script can be used on all computers that have software to interpret the script.
[src:cocos2d/cross-platform-software] This is because the script is generally stored in plain text in a text file.
[src:cocos2d/cross-platform-software] There may be some trivial issues, such as the representation of a new line character.
[src:cocos2d/cross-platform-software] Cross-platform or multi-platform is a term that can also apply to video games released on a range of video game consoles.
[src:cocos2d/cross-platform-software] Examples of cross-platform games include: *Miner 2049er*, *Tomb Raider: Legend*, *FIFA series*, *NHL series* and *Minecraft*.
[src:cocos2d/cross-platform-software] Each has been released across a variety of gaming platforms, such as the Wii, PlayStation 3, Xbox 360, personal computers, and mobile devices.
[src:cocos2d/cross-platform-software] Some platforms are harder to write for than others, requiring more time to develop the video game to the same standard.
[src:cocos2d/cross-platform-software] To offset this, a video game may be released on a few platforms first, then later on others.
[src:cocos2d/cross-platform-software] Typically, this happens when a new gaming system is released, because video game developers need to acquaint themselves with its hardware and software.
[src:cocos2d/cross-platform-software] Some games may not be cross-platform because of licensing agreements between developers and video game console manufacturers that limit development to one particular console.
[src:cocos2d/cross-platform-software] As an example, Disney could create a game with the intention of release on the latest Nintendo and Sony game consoles.
[src:cocos2d/cross-platform-software] Should Disney license the game with Sony first, it may be required to release the game solely on Sony's console for a short time or indefinitely.
[src:cocos2d/cross-platform-software] Several developers have implemented ways to play games online while using different platforms.
[src:cocos2d/cross-platform-software] Psyonix, Epic Games, Microsoft, and Valve all possess technology that allows Xbox 360 and PlayStation 3 gamers to play with PC gamers, leaving the decision of which platform to use to consumers.
[src:cocos2d/cross-platform-software] The first game to allow this level of interactivity between PC and console games (Dreamcast with specially produced keyboard and mouse) was *Quake 3*.
[src:cocos2d/cross-platform-software] Games that feature cross-platform online play include *Rocket League*, *Final Fantasy XIV*, *Street Fighter V*, *Killer Instinct*, *Paragon* and *Fable Fortune,* and *Minecraft* with its Better Together update on Windows 10, VR editions, Pocket Edition and Xbox One.
[src:cocos2d/cross-platform-software] Cross-platform programming is the practice of deliberately writing software to work on more than one platform.
[src:cocos2d/cross-platform-software] There are different ways to write a cross-platform application.
[src:cocos2d/cross-platform-software] One approach is to create multiple versions of the same software in different *source trees*—in other words, the Microsoft Windows version of an application might have one set of source code files and the Macintosh version another, while a FOSS *nix system might have a third.
[src:cocos2d/cross-platform-software] While this is straightforward, compared to developing for only one platform it can cost much more to pay a larger team or release products more slowly.
[src:cocos2d/cross-platform-software] It can also result in more bugs to be tracked and fixed.
[src:cocos2d/cross-platform-software] Another approach is to use software that hides the differences between the platforms.
[src:cocos2d/cross-platform-software] This abstraction layer insulates the application from the platform.
[src:cocos2d/cross-platform-software] Such applications are *platform agnostic*.
[src:cocos2d/cross-platform-software] Applications that run on the JVM are built this way.
[src:cocos2d/cross-platform-software] Some applications mix various methods of cross-platform programming to create the final application.
[src:cocos2d/cross-platform-software] An example is the Firefox web browser, which uses abstraction to build some of the lower-level components, with separate source subtrees for implementing platform-specific features (like the GUI), and the implementation of more than one scripting language to ease software portability.
[src:cocos2d/cross-platform-software] Firefox implements XUL, CSS and JavaScript for extending the browser, in addition to classic Netscape-style browser plugins.
[src:cocos2d/cross-platform-software] Much of the browser itself is written in XUL, CSS, and JavaScript.
[src:cocos2d/game-engine] A **game engine** is a software framework primarily designed for video game development, which may include specialized software libraries and packages, such as level editors.
[src:cocos2d/game-engine] The term "engine" is a direct analogue of "software engine", having it employed across sectors of the software industry.
[src:cocos2d/game-engine] Furthermore, *game engine* may also refer to the integrated development environment as an interface behind the given framework, typically a suite of visual development tools and features for developing video games.
[src:cocos2d/game-engine] Game developers can use game engines to create and publish video games across platforms, such as desktops, mobile devices, video game consoles, and other types of computers.
[src:cocos2d/game-engine] The core functionalities commonly covered by a game engine are a 2D or 3D renderer, physics engine, audio engine, scripting, animation, artificial intelligence, networking, streaming, memory management, threads, localization support, scene graph, and cinematics.
[src:cocos2d/game-engine] Game engine developers often economize game development through reuse or adaptation of abstractions built into game engines for production of various games, or through porting of videogames from a single to other target platforms.
[src:cocos2d/game-engine] In many cases, game engines provide a suite of visual development tools in addition to reusable software components.
[src:cocos2d/game-engine] These tools are generally provided in an integrated development environment to enable simplified, rapid development of games in a data-driven manner.
[src:cocos2d/game-engine] Game-engine developers often attempt to preempt implementer needs by developing robust software suites, which include many elements a game developer may need to build a game.
[src:cocos2d/game-engine] Most game-engine suites provide facilities that ease development, such as graphics, sound, physics and artificial intelligence (AI) functions.
[src:cocos2d/game-engine] Like other types of middleware, game engines usually provide platform abstraction, allowing the same game to run on various platforms (including game consoles and personal computers) with few, if any, changes made to the game source code.
[src:cocos2d/game-engine] Often, programmers design game engines with a component-based architecture that allows specific systems in the engine to be replaced or extended with more specialized (and often more expensive) game-middleware components.
[src:cocos2d/game-engine] Some game engines comprise a series of loosely-connected game middleware components that can be selectively combined to create a custom engine, instead of the more common approach of extending or customizing a flexible integrated product.
[src:cocos2d/game-engine] However achieved, extensibility remains a high priority for game engines due to the wide variety of uses for which they are applied.
[src:cocos2d/game-engine] Despite the specificity of the name "game engine", end users often re-purpose game engines for other kinds of interactive applications with real-time graphical requirements—such as marketing demos, architectural visualizations, training simulations, and modeling environments.
[src:cocos2d/game-engine] Some game engines only provide real-time 3D rendering capabilities instead of the wide range of functionality needed by games.
[src:cocos2d/game-engine] These engines rely upon the game developer to implement the rest of this functionality or to assemble it from other game-middleware components.
[src:cocos2d/game-engine] These types of engines are generally referred to as a "graphics engine", "rendering engine", or "3D engine" instead of the all-encompassing term "game engine".
[src:cocos2d/game-engine] This terminology is inconsistently used, as many full-featured 3D game engines are simply referred to as "3D engines".
[src:cocos2d/game-engine] Examples of graphics engines include: Crystal Space, Genesis3D, Irrlicht, OGRE, RealmForge, Truevision3D, and Vision Engine.
[src:cocos2d/game-engine] Modern game- or graphics-engines generally provide a scene graph—an object-oriented representation of the 3D game-world which often simplifies game design and can be used for more efficient rendering of vast virtual worlds.
[src:cocos2d/game-engine] Most game engines or graphics engines use a Graphics API, which eases communication with the GPU.
[src:cocos2d/game-engine] But older games did not have hardware acceleration or GPUs and had to build their own software renderer.
[src:cocos2d/game-engine] As technology ages, the components of an engine may become obsolete or insufficient for the requirements of a given project.
[src:cocos2d/game-engine] Since the complexity of programming an entirely new engine may result in unwanted delays (or necessitate that a project restart from the beginning), an engine-development team may elect to update their existing engine with newer functionality or components.
[src:cocos2d/game-engine] Game engines are not limited to use in the video game field, and have found uses in other scientific fields.
[src:cocos2d/game-engine] Part of this is due to game engines being optimized for consumer-grade computing equipment rather than high-performance computing, allowing researchers to develop programs for their use on lower cost machines.
[src:cocos2d/game-engine] Game engines also simplify many of the computing operations needed for scientific software, including graphics, networking, and interactivity, reducing the need to develop these features themselves.
[src:cocos2d/game-engine] Before game engines, games were typically written as singular entities: a game for the Atari 2600, for example, had to be designed from the bottom up to make optimal use of the display hardware—this core display routine is now called the kernel by developers of games for older systems.
[src:cocos2d/game-engine] Other platforms had more leeway, but even when display was not a concern, memory constraints usually sabotaged attempts to create the data-heavy design that an engine needs.
[src:cocos2d/game-engine] Even on more accommodating platforms, very little could be reused between games.
[src:cocos2d/game-engine] The rapid advance of arcade hardware—which was the leading edge of the market at the time—meant that most of the code would have to be thrown out afterwards anyway, as later generations of games would use completely different game designs that took advantage of extra resources.
[src:cocos2d/game-engine] Thus, most game designs through the 1980s were designed through a hard-coded rule set with a small number of levels and graphics data.
[src:cocos2d/game-engine] Since the golden age of arcade video games, it became common for video game companies to develop in-house game engines for use with first-party software.
[src:cocos2d/game-engine] A notable example of an in-house game engine on home consoles in the mid-1980s was the smooth side-scrolling engine developed by Shigeru Miyamoto's team at Nintendo for the Nintendo Entertainment System (NES).
[src:cocos2d/game-engine] The engine they had developed for the side-scrolling racing game *Excitebike* (1984) was later employed for the scrolling platformer *Super Mario Bros.* (1985).
[src:cocos2d/game-engine] This allowed Mario to smoothly accelerate from a walk to a run, rather than move at a constant speed like in earlier platformers.
[src:cocos2d/game-engine] While third-party game engines were not common until the rise of 3D computer graphics in the 1990s, several 2D game creation systems were produced in the 1980s for independent video game development.
[src:cocos2d/game-engine] Klik & Play (1994) is another legacy offering that is still available.
[src:cocos2d/game-engine] The term *game engine* emerged in the mid-1990s, particularly with the rise of 3D games like first-person shooters, which often featured a dedicated first-person shooter engine.
[src:cocos2d/game-engine] For instance, Epic Games, founded by Tim Sweeney, debuted its Unreal Engine in 1998.
[src:cocos2d/game-engine] Later games, such as id Software's *Quake III Arena* and Epic Games' *Unreal* (1998), were designed with this approach in mind, with the engine and content developed separately.
[src:cocos2d/game-engine] At the very least, reusable engines make developing game sequels faster and easier, which is a valuable advantage in the competitive video game industry.
[src:cocos2d/game-engine] While a strong rivalry existed between Epic Games and id Software around 2000, Epic Game's Unreal Engine has since become far more popular than id Tech 4 and its successor, id Tech 5.
[src:cocos2d/game-engine] Modern game engines are some of the most complex applications written, often featuring dozens of finely-tuned systems interacting to ensure a precisely-controlled user experience.
[src:cocos2d/game-engine] The continued evolution of game engines has created a strong separation between rendering, scripting, artwork, and level design.
[src:cocos2d/game-engine] As such, it is now common, for example, for a typical game development team to have several times as many artists as actual programmers.
[src:cocos2d/game-engine] While third-party game engines are predominantly used in the development of first-person shooter games, they are also being used across other genres.
[src:cocos2d/game-engine] For example, Gamebryo is used in *The Elder Scrolls III: Morrowind* and *Dark Age of Camelot*, whereas Unreal Engine 2 is used in *Lineage II*.
[src:cocos2d/game-engine] Game engines are also used for games originally developed for home consoles, with RenderWare for the *Grand Theft Auto* and *Burnout* franchises as an example.
[src:cocos2d/game-engine] Due to modern multi-core systems and growing demands in realism, exploiting threads has become more important.
[src:cocos2d/game-engine] Separate threads of execution within a game engine manage intensive operations, including rendering, asset streaming, audio playback, and physics simulation.
[src:cocos2d/game-engine] Racing games have typically been at the forefront of threading with the physics engine running in a separate thread long before other core subsystems were moved, partly because rendering and related tasks need updating at only 30–60 Hz.
[src:cocos2d/game-engine] For example, on PlayStation 3, physics ran in *Need For Speed* at 100 Hz, versus *Forza Motorsport 2* at 360 Hz.
[src:cocos2d/game-engine] Although the term was first used in the 1990s, few earlier systems in 1980s are considered as game engines, such as Sierra's Adventure Game Interpreter (AGI) and SCI systems, LucasArts' SCUMM system and Incentive Software's Freescape engine (in 1986).
[src:cocos2d/game-engine] Unlike most modern game engines, these game engines were never used in any third-party products (except for the SCUMM system, which was licensed to and used by Humongous Entertainment).
[src:cocos2d/game-engine] As game engine technology matures and becomes more user friendly, the application of game engines has widened in scope.
[src:cocos2d/game-engine] They are now used for serious games: visualization, training, medical, and military simulation applications, with the CryEngine being one example.
[src:cocos2d/game-engine] To improve accessibility, new hardware platforms are also now targeted by game engines, including mobile phones (e.g.
[src:cocos2d/game-engine] Additionally, more game engines are being built upon higher-level languages, such as Java, C# and .NET (e.g., TorqueX, and Visual3D.NET), Python (Panda3D), or Lua Script (Leadwerks).
[src:cocos2d/game-engine] As most 3D-rich games are now mostly limited by the power of a graphics card, the potential slowdown due to translation overheads of higher-level languages becomes negligible, while productivity gains offered by these languages serve the game engine developers' benefit.
[src:cocos2d/game-engine] These recent trends are being propelled by companies such as Microsoft to support indie game development.
[src:cocos2d/game-engine] Microsoft developed XNA as the primary Software Development Kit (SDK) for all video games released on Xbox and their related products.
[src:cocos2d/game-engine] This includes the Xbox Live Indie Games channel designed specifically for smaller developers who do not have the extensive resources necessary to box games for sale on retail shelves.
[src:cocos2d/game-engine] It is becoming easier and cheaper than ever to develop game engines for platforms that support managed frameworks.
[src:cocos2d/game-engine] Producers of game engines decide how they allow users to use their products.
[src:cocos2d/game-engine] Just as gaming is an industry, so are the engines they are built off.
[src:cocos2d/game-engine] The major game engines come at varying prices, whether it be in the form of subscription fees or license payments.
[src:cocos2d/game-engine] Unity and Unreal Engine are currently the two most popular choices for game developers.
[src:cocos2d/game-engine] Although the differences among the different game engines blur as they build their own tools on top of them, different game developers may be too used to a system to change, or attracted by the huge benefits of such engines regardless of pay-walls.
[src:cocos2d/game-engine] Free and open-source engines such as Godot, have seen a rise in popularity, particularly following the 2023 Unity pricing controversy which drove game developers and studios to seek engines with a permissive license.
[src:cocos2d/game-engine] Applied more broadly, game engines themselves can be described as middleware.
[src:cocos2d/game-engine] In video games, however, *middleware* is often used to refer to subsystems of functionality within a game engine.
[src:cocos2d/game-engine] Some game middleware does only one thing, yet does it more convincingly or more efficiently than general purpose middleware.
[src:cocos2d/game-engine] The four most-widely used middleware packages that provide subsystems of functionality include RAD Game Tools' Bink, Firelight FMOD, Havok, and Scaleform GFx.
[src:cocos2d/game-engine] RAD Game Tools develops Bink for basic video rendering, along with Miles audio, and Granny 3D rendering.
[src:cocos2d/game-engine] Firelight FMOD is a low cost robust audio library and toolset.
[src:cocos2d/game-engine] Havok provides a robust physics simulation system, along with a suite of animation and behavior applications.
[src:cocos2d/game-engine] Scaleform provides GFx for high performance Flash UI and high-quality video playback, and an Input Method Editor (IME) addon for in-game Asian chat support.
[src:cocos2d/game-engine] Other middleware is used for performance optimization—for example Simplygon helps to optimize and generate level of detail meshes, and Umbra adds occlusion culling optimizations to 3D graphics.
[src:cocos2d/game-engine] Some middleware contains full source code, or is provided an API reference for a compiled binary library.
[src:cocos2d/game-engine] Some middleware programs can be licensed either way, usually for a higher fee for full source code.
[src:cocos2d/opengl] (SGI) began developing OpenGL in 1991 and released it on June 30, 1992.
[src:cocos2d/opengl] It is used for a variety of applications, including computer-aided design (CAD), video games, scientific visualization, virtual reality, and flight simulation.
[src:cocos2d/opengl] Since 2006, OpenGL has been managed by the non-profit technology consortium Khronos Group.
[src:cocos2d/opengl] The OpenGL specification describes an abstract application programming interface (API) for drawing 2D and 3D graphics.
[src:cocos2d/opengl] It is designed to be implemented mostly or entirely using hardware acceleration such as a GPU, although it is possible for the API to be implemented entirely in software running on a CPU.
[src:cocos2d/opengl] The API is defined as a set of functions which may be called by the client program, alongside a set of named integer constants (for example, the constant GL_TEXTURE_2D, which corresponds to the decimal number 3553).
[src:cocos2d/opengl] Although the function definitions are superficially similar to those of the programming language C, they are language-independent.
[src:cocos2d/opengl] As such, OpenGL has many language bindings, some of the most noteworthy being the JavaScript binding WebGL (API, based on OpenGL ES 2.0, for 3D rendering from within a web browser); the C bindings WGL, GLX and CGL; the C binding provided by iOS; and the Java and C bindings provided by Android.
[src:cocos2d/opengl] In addition to being language-independent, OpenGL is also cross-platform.
[src:cocos2d/opengl] The specification says nothing on the subject of obtaining and managing an OpenGL context, leaving this as a detail of the underlying windowing system.
[src:cocos2d/opengl] For the same reason, OpenGL is purely concerned with rendering, providing no APIs related to input, audio, or windowing.
[src:cocos2d/opengl] New versions of the OpenGL specifications are released by the Khronos Group, each of which extends the API to support various new features.
[src:cocos2d/opengl] The details of each version are decided by consensus between the Group's members, including graphics card manufacturers, operating system designers, and general technology companies such as Mozilla and Google.
[src:cocos2d/opengl] In addition to the features required by the core API, graphics processing unit (GPU) vendors may provide additional functionality in the form of *extensions*.
[src:cocos2d/opengl] Extensions may introduce new functions and new constants, and may relax or remove restrictions on existing OpenGL functions.
[src:cocos2d/opengl] Vendors can use extensions to expose custom APIs without needing support from other vendors or the Khronos Group as a whole, which greatly increases the flexibility of OpenGL.
[src:cocos2d/opengl] All extensions are collected in, and defined by, the OpenGL Registry.
[src:cocos2d/opengl] The features introduced by each new version of OpenGL are typically formed from the combined features of several widely implemented extensions, especially extensions of type ARB or EXT.
[src:cocos2d/opengl] OpenGL is no longer in active development; whereas between 2001 and 2014, OpenGL specification was updated mostly on a yearly basis, with two releases (3.1 and 3.2) taking place in 2009 and three (3.3, 4.0 and 4.1) in 2010.
[src:cocos2d/opengl] The latest OpenGL specification 4.6 was released in 2017 after a three-year break, and was limited to inclusion of eleven existing ARB and EXT extensions into the core profile.
[src:cocos2d/opengl] Active development of OpenGL was dropped in favor of the Vulkan API, released in 2016, and codenamed glNext during initial development.
[src:cocos2d/opengl] In 2017, Khronos Group announced that OpenGL ES would not have new versions and has since concentrated on development of Vulkan and other technologies.
[src:cocos2d/opengl] As a result, certain capabilities offered by modern GPUs, e.g. ray tracing, are not supported by the OpenGL standard.
[src:cocos2d/opengl] However, support for newer features might be provided through the vendor-specific OpenGL extensions.
[src:cocos2d/opengl] The OpenGL Architecture Review Board released a series of manuals along with the specification which have been updated to track changes in the API.
[src:cocos2d/opengl] OpenGL Programming for the X Window System.
[src:cocos2d/opengl] Includes a poster-sized fold-out diagram showing the structure of an idealised OpenGL implementation.
[src:cocos2d/opengl] OpenGL Programming for Windows 95 and Windows NT.
[src:cocos2d/opengl] A book about interfacing OpenGL with Microsoft Windows.
[src:cocos2d/opengl] OpenGL's documentation is also accessible via its official webpage.
[src:cocos2d/opengl] The earliest versions of OpenGL were released with a companion library called the OpenGL Utility Library (GLU).
[src:cocos2d/opengl] It provided simple, useful features which were unlikely to be supported in contemporary hardware, such as tessellating, and generating mipmaps and primitive shapes.
[src:cocos2d/opengl] The GLU specification was last updated in 1998 and depends on OpenGL features which are now deprecated.
[src:cocos2d/opengl] Given that creating an OpenGL context is quite a complex process, and given that it varies between operating systems, automatic OpenGL context creation has become a common feature of several game-development and user-interface libraries, including SDL, Allegro, SFML, FLTK, and Qt.
[src:cocos2d/opengl] A few libraries have been designed solely to produce an OpenGL-capable window.
[src:cocos2d/opengl] The first such library was OpenGL Utility Toolkit (GLUT), later superseded by freeglut.
[src:cocos2d/opengl] Given the high workload involved in identifying and loading OpenGL extensions, a few libraries have been designed which load all available extensions and functions automatically.
[src:cocos2d/opengl] Examples include OpenGL Easy Extension library (GLEE), OpenGL Extension Wrangler Library (GLEW) and glbinding.
[src:cocos2d/opengl] Extensions are also loaded automatically by most language bindings, such as Java OpenGL, PyOpenGL and WebGL.
[src:cocos2d/opengl] Mesa 3D is an open-source implementation of OpenGL.
[src:cocos2d/opengl] It can do pure software rendering, and it may also use hardware acceleration on BSD, Linux, and other platforms by taking advantage of the Direct Rendering Infrastructure.
[src:cocos2d/opengl] As of version 20.0, it implements version 4.6 of the OpenGL standard.
[src:cocos2d/opengl] In the 1980s, developing software that could function with a wide range of graphics hardware was a challenge without a cross-platform library.
[src:cocos2d/opengl] Software developers wrote custom interfaces and drivers for each piece of hardware.
[src:cocos2d/opengl] This was expensive and resulted in multiplication of effort.
[src:cocos2d/opengl] By the early 1990s, Silicon Graphics (SGI) was a leader in 3D graphics for workstations.
[src:cocos2d/opengl] Their IRIS GL API became the industry standard, as IRIS GL was considered easier to use, and it supported immediate mode rendering, therefore being faster than competitors like PHIGS.
[src:cocos2d/opengl] SGI's competitors (including Sun Microsystems, Hewlett-Packard and IBM) were also able to bring to market 3D hardware supported by extensions made to the PHIGS standard, which pressured SGI to open source a version of IRIS GL as a public standard called **OpenGL**.
[src:cocos2d/opengl] However, SGI had many customers for whom the change from IRIS GL to OpenGL would demand significant investment.
[src:cocos2d/opengl] Moreover, IRIS GL had API functions that were irrelevant to 3D graphics.
[src:cocos2d/opengl] For example, it included a windowing, keyboard and mouse API, in part because it was developed before the X Window System and Sun's NeWS.
[src:cocos2d/opengl] IRIS GL libraries were heavily tied into SGI's proprietary graphics hardware and could not be open sourced as-is due to hardware patents and trade secrets.
[src:cocos2d/opengl] These factors required SGI to continue to support the advanced and proprietary Iris Inventor and Iris Performer programming APIs while market support for OpenGL matured.
[src:cocos2d/opengl] One of the restrictions of IRIS GL was that it only provided access to features supported by the underlying hardware.
[src:cocos2d/opengl] If the graphics hardware did not support a feature natively, then the application could not use it.
[src:cocos2d/opengl] OpenGL overcame this problem by providing software implementations of features unsupported by hardware, allowing applications to use advanced graphics on relatively low-powered systems.
[src:cocos2d/opengl] OpenGL standardized access to hardware, pushed the development responsibility of hardware interface programs (device drivers) to hardware manufacturers, and delegated windowing functions to the underlying operating system.
[src:cocos2d/opengl] With so many different kinds of graphics hardware, getting them all to speak the same language in this way had a remarkable impact by giving software developers a higher-level platform for 3D-software development.
[src:cocos2d/opengl] In 1992, SGI led the creation of the OpenGL Architecture Review Board (OpenGL ARB), the group of companies that would maintain and expand the OpenGL specification in the future.
[src:cocos2d/opengl] Two years later, they also played with the idea of releasing something called "OpenGL++" which included elements such as a scene-graph API (presumably based on their Performer technology).
[src:cocos2d/opengl] The specification was circulated among a few interested parties – but never turned into a product.
[src:cocos2d/opengl] Released in 1996, Microsoft's Direct3D eventually became the main competitor of OpenGL.
[src:cocos2d/opengl] Over 50 game developers signed an open letter to Microsoft, released on June 12, 1997, calling on the company to actively support OpenGL.
[src:cocos2d/opengl] On December 17, 1997, Microsoft and SGI initiated the Fahrenheit project, which was a joint effort with the goal of unifying the OpenGL and Direct3D interfaces (and adding a scene-graph API too).
[src:cocos2d/opengl] In 1998, Hewlett-Packard joined the project.
[src:cocos2d/opengl] It initially showed some promise of bringing order to the world of interactive 3D computer graphics APIs, but on account of financial constraints at SGI, strategic reasons at Microsoft, and a general lack of industry support, it was abandoned in 1999.
[src:cocos2d/opengl] In July 2006, the OpenGL Architecture Review Board voted to transfer control of the OpenGL API standard to the Khronos Group.
[src:cocos2d/opengl] OpenGL was the standard for many CAD software (such as Blender) and games in the 1990s and 2000s, and faces wide support across virtually all hardware vendors.
[src:cocos2d/opengl] Despite the emergence of newer graphics APIs like its successor Vulkan or Metal, OpenGL continues to be a widely used standard.
[src:cocos2d/opengl] This continued relevance is supported by several factors: ongoing development with new extensions and driver optimizations, its cross-platform compatibility, and the availability of compatibility layers like ANGLE and Zink.
[src:cocos2d/opengl] These layers allow OpenGL to run efficiently on top of Vulkan and Metal, offering a pathway for continued use or gradual transitions for developers.
[src:cocos2d/opengl] However, the graphics API landscape has been shifting, where some companies are moving away from OpenGL.
[src:cocos2d/opengl] In June 2018, Apple deprecated OpenGL APIs on all of their platforms (iOS, macOS and tvOS), encouraging developers to use their proprietary Metal API, which was introduced in 2014.
[src:cocos2d/opengl] Game developers have also begun to adopt newer APIs. id Software, who has been using OpenGL in their games since the late 1990s in games such as GLQuake or some games of the Doom franchise, transitioned away to its successor Vulkan in its id Tech 7 engine in 2016.
[src:cocos2d/opengl] They first supported Vulkan in an update for their id Tech 6 engine.
[src:cocos2d/opengl] The company's first licensed use of OpenGL was in its Quake II engine, also known as id Tech 2.
[src:cocos2d/opengl] In March 2023, Valve removed OpenGL support from Dota 2 in favor of Vulkan.
[src:cocos2d/opengl] Atypical Games, with support from Samsung, updated their game engine to use Vulkan, rather than OpenGL, across all non-Apple platforms.
[src:cocos2d/opengl] The Khronos Group, the consortium responsible for OpenGL's development, has stopped updating OpenGL, with the last release made in 2017.
[src:cocos2d/opengl] It has not received a number of modern graphics technologies, such as hardware accelerated Ray Tracing, on-GPU video decoding, and advanced anti-aliasing algorithms like Nvidia DLSS and AMD FSR.
[src:cocos2d/opengl] Another modern feature, Mesh Shaders, was initially only supported through an Nvidia exclusive extension, however in 2025, a cross-vendor OpenGL Mesh Shader extension was released.
[src:cocos2d/opengl] Google's Fuchsia OS, while using Vulkan natively and requiring a Vulkan-conformant GPU, still intends to support OpenGL on top of Vulkan via the ANGLE translation layer.
[src:cocos2d/opengl] The first version of OpenGL, version 1.0, was released on June 30, 1992, by Mark Segal and Kurt Akeley.
[src:cocos2d/opengl] Since then, OpenGL has occasionally been extended by releasing a new version of the specification.
[src:cocos2d/opengl] Such releases define a baseline set of features which all conforming graphics cards must support, and against which new extensions can more easily be written.
[src:cocos2d/opengl] Each new version of OpenGL tends to incorporate several extensions which have widespread support among graphics-card vendors, although the details of those extensions may be changed.
[src:cocos2d/opengl] OpenGL 2.0 was originally conceived by 3Dlabs to address concerns that OpenGL was stagnating and lacked a strong direction.
[src:cocos2d/opengl] 3Dlabs proposed a number of major additions to the standard.
[src:cocos2d/opengl] Most of these were, at the time, rejected by the ARB or otherwise never came to fruition in the form that 3Dlabs proposed.
[src:cocos2d/opengl] However, their proposal for a C-style shading language was eventually completed, resulting in the current formulation of the OpenGL Shading Language (GLSL or GLslang).
[src:cocos2d/opengl] Like the assembly-like shading languages it was replacing, it allowed replacing the fixed-function vertex and fragment pipe with shaders, though this time written in a C-like high-level language.
[src:cocos2d/opengl] The design of GLSL was notable for making relatively few concessions to the limits of the hardware then available.
[src:cocos2d/opengl] This harked back to the earlier tradition of OpenGL setting an ambitious, forward-looking target for 3D accelerators rather than merely tracking the state of currently available hardware.
[src:cocos2d/opengl] The final OpenGL 2.0 specification includes support for GLSL 1.10.
[src:cocos2d/opengl] OpenGL 2.1 adds support for Pixel Buffer Objects, sRGB textures and GLSL 1.20.
[src:cocos2d/opengl] Before the release of OpenGL 3.0, the new revision had the codename Longs Peak.
[src:cocos2d/opengl] At the time of its original announcement, Longs Peak was presented as the first major API revision in OpenGL's lifetime.
[src:cocos2d/opengl] It consisted of an overhaul to the way that OpenGL works, calling for fundamental changes to the API.
[src:cocos2d/opengl] The draft introduced a change to object management.
[src:cocos2d/opengl] The GL 2.1 object model was built upon the state-based design of OpenGL.
[src:cocos2d/opengl] That is, to modify an object or to use it, one needs to bind the object to the state system, then make modifications to the state or perform function calls that use the bound object.
[src:cocos2d/opengl] Because of OpenGL's use of a state system, objects must be mutable.
[src:cocos2d/opengl] That is, the basic structure of an object can change at any time, even if the rendering pipeline is asynchronously using that object.
[src:cocos2d/opengl] A texture object can be redefined from 2D to 3D.
[src:cocos2d/opengl] This requires any OpenGL implementations to add a degree of complexity to internal object management.
[src:cocos2d/opengl] Under the Longs Peak API, object creation would become atomic, using templates to define the properties of an object which would be created with one function call.
[src:cocos2d/opengl] The object could then be used immediately across multiple threads.
[src:cocos2d/opengl] Objects would also be immutable; however, they could have their contents changed and updated.
[src:cocos2d/opengl] For example, a texture could change its image, but its size and format could not be changed.
[src:cocos2d/opengl] To support backwards compatibility, the old state based API would still be available, but no new functionality would be exposed via the old API in later versions of OpenGL.
[src:cocos2d/opengl] This would have allowed legacy code bases, such as the majority of CAD products, to continue to run while other software could be written against or ported to the new API.
[src:cocos2d/opengl] Longs Peak was initially due to be finalized in September 2007 under the name OpenGL 3.0, but the Khronos Group announced on October 30 that it had run into several issues that it wished to address before releasing the specification.
[src:cocos2d/opengl] As a result, the spec was delayed, and the Khronos Group went into a media blackout until the release of the final OpenGL 3.0 spec.
[src:cocos2d/opengl] The final specification proved far less revolutionary than the Longs Peak proposal.
[src:cocos2d/opengl] Instead of removing all immediate mode and fixed functionality (non-shader mode), the spec included them as deprecated features.
[src:cocos2d/opengl] The proposed object model was not included, and no plans have been announced to include it in any future revisions.
[src:cocos2d/opengl] As a result, the API remained largely the same with a few existing extensions being promoted to core functionality.
[src:cocos2d/opengl] Among some developer groups this decision caused something of an uproar, with many developers professing that they would switch to DirectX in protest.
[src:cocos2d/opengl] Most complaints revolved around the lack of communication by Khronos to the development community and multiple features being discarded that were viewed favorably by many.
[src:cocos2d/opengl] Other frustrations included the requirement of DirectX 10 level hardware to use OpenGL 3.0 and the absence of geometry shaders and instanced rendering as core features.
[src:cocos2d/opengl] Other sources reported that the community reaction was not quite as severe as originally presented, with many vendors showing support for the update.
[src:cocos2d/opengl] OpenGL 3.0 introduced a deprecation mechanism to simplify future revisions of the API.
[src:cocos2d/opengl] Certain features, marked as deprecated, could be completely disabled by requesting a *forward-compatible context* from the windowing system.
[src:cocos2d/opengl] OpenGL 3.0 features could still be accessed alongside these deprecated features, however, by requesting a *full context*.
[src:cocos2d/opengl] Hardware support: Nvidia GeForce 8 Series and newer, ATI Radeon HD 2000 series and newer, Intel HD Graphics in Intel Sandy Bridge processors and newer.
[src:cocos2d/opengl] OpenGL 3.1 fully removed all of the features which were deprecated in version 3.0, with the exception of wide lines.
[src:cocos2d/opengl] From this version onwards, it's not possible to access new features using a *full context*, or to access deprecated features using a *forward-compatible context*.
[src:cocos2d/opengl] An exception to the former rule is made if the implementation supports the ARB_compatibility extension, but this is not guaranteed.
[src:cocos2d/opengl] Hardware support: Mesa supports ARM Panfrost with Version 21.0.
[src:cocos2d/opengl] OpenGL 3.2 further built on the deprecation mechanisms introduced by OpenGL 3.0, by dividing the specification into a *core profile* and *compatibility profile*.
[src:cocos2d/opengl] Compatibility contexts include the previously removed fixed-function APIs, equivalent to the ARB_compatibility extension released alongside OpenGL 3.1, while core contexts do not.
[src:cocos2d/opengl] OpenGL 3.2 also included an upgrade to GLSL version 1.50.
[src:cocos2d/opengl] OpenGL 3.3 includes minor additions, with the goal of retaining as much functionality as possible from OpenGL 4.0, while keeping support for older hardware.
[src:cocos2d/opengl] Additions include new blending functions, Sampler Objects and new texture and vertex formats.
[src:cocos2d/opengl] Support is also added for GLSL version 3.30, major and minor versions now match with OpenGL.
[src:cocos2d/opengl] OpenGL 4.0 was released alongside version 3.3.
[src:cocos2d/opengl] It was designed for hardware able to support Direct3D 11.
[src:cocos2d/opengl] As in OpenGL 3.0, this version of OpenGL contains a high number of fairly inconsequential extensions, designed to thoroughly expose the abilities of Direct3D 11-class hardware, such as tessellation.
[src:cocos2d/opengl] Hardware support: Nvidia GeForce 400 series and newer, AMD Radeon HD 5000 series and newer (FP64 shaders implemented by emulation on some TeraScale GPUs), Intel HD Graphics in Intel Ivy Bridge processors and newer.
[src:cocos2d/opengl] Hardware support: Nvidia GeForce 400 series and newer, AMD Radeon HD 5000 series and newer (FP64 shaders implemented by emulation on some TeraScale GPUs), Intel HD Graphics in Intel Haswell processors and newer (Linux Mesa: Ivy Bridge and newer).
[src:cocos2d/opengl] Additionally, this is the last core profile supported by Apple macOS.
[src:cocos2d/opengl] Hardware support: Nvidia GeForce 400 series and newer, AMD Radeon HD 5000 series and newer (FP64 shaders implemented by emulation on some TeraScale GPUs), and Intel HD Graphics in Intel Haswell processors and newer.
[src:cocos2d/opengl] Hardware support: AMD Radeon HD 5000 series and newer (FP64 shaders implemented by emulation on some TeraScale GPUs), Intel HD Graphics in Intel Haswell processors and newer.
[src:cocos2d/opengl] (Linux Mesa: Ivy Bridge without stencil texturing, Haswell and newer), Nvidia GeForce 400 series and newer.
[src:cocos2d/opengl] VIRGL Emulation for virtual machines supports 4.3+ with Mesa 20.
[src:cocos2d/opengl] Hardware support: AMD Radeon HD 5000 series and newer (FP64 shaders implemented by emulation on some TeraScale GPUs), Intel HD Graphics in Intel Broadwell processors and newer (Linux Mesa: Haswell and newer), Nvidia GeForce 400 series and newer, Tegra K1.
[src:cocos2d/opengl] Hardware support: AMD Radeon HD 5000 series and newer (FP64 shaders implemented by emulation on some TeraScale GPUs), Intel HD Graphics in Intel Broadwell processors and newer (Linux Mesa: Haswell and newer), Nvidia GeForce 400 series and newer, Tegra K1, and Tegra X1.
[src:cocos2d/opengl] Hardware support: AMD Radeon HD 7000 series and newer (FP64 shaders implemented by emulation on some TeraScale GPUs), Intel Skylake and newer, Nvidia GeForce 400 series and newer.
[src:cocos2d/opengl] Apple deprecated OpenGL in iOS 12 and macOS 10.14 Mojave in favor of Metal, but it is still available as of macOS 15 Sequoia (including on Apple silicon devices).
[src:cocos2d/opengl] The latest version supported for OpenGL is 4.1 from 2011.
[src:cocos2d/opengl] A proprietary library from Molten – authors of MoltenVK – called MoltenGL, can translate OpenGL calls to Metal.
[src:cocos2d/opengl] There are several projects that attempt to implement OpenGL on top of Vulkan.
[src:cocos2d/opengl] The Vulkan backend for Google's ANGLE achieved OpenGL ES 3.1 conformance in July 2020.
[src:cocos2d/opengl] The Mesa3D project also includes such a driver, called *Zink*.
[src:cocos2d/opengl] Microsoft's Windows 11 on Arm added support for OpenGL 3.3 via GLon12, an open source OpenGL implementation on top DirectX 12 via Mesa Gallium.
[src:cocos2d/opengl] Vulkan, formerly named the "Next Generation OpenGL Initiative" (glNext), is a ground-up redesign effort to unify OpenGL and OpenGL ES into one common API that will not be backwards compatible with existing OpenGL versions.
[src:cocos2d/opengl] The initial version of Vulkan API was released on February 16, 2016.
[src:cocos2d/sprite-computer-graphics] In computer graphics, a **sprite** is a two-dimensional bitmap that is integrated into a larger scene, most often in a 2D video game.
[src:cocos2d/sprite-computer-graphics] Originally, the term *sprite* referred to fixed-sized objects composited together, by hardware, with a background.
[src:cocos2d/sprite-computer-graphics] Use of the term has since become more general.
[src:cocos2d/sprite-computer-graphics] Hardware varies in the number of sprites supported, the size and colors of each sprite, and special effects such as scaling or reporting pixel-precise overlap.
[src:cocos2d/sprite-computer-graphics] Hardware composition of sprites occurs as each scan line is prepared for the video output device, such as a cathode-ray tube, without involvement of the main CPU and without the need for a full-screen frame buffer.
[src:cocos2d/sprite-computer-graphics] Sprites can be positioned or altered by setting attributes used during the hardware composition process.
[src:cocos2d/sprite-computer-graphics] The number of sprites which can be displayed per scan line is often lower than the total number of sprites a system supports.
[src:cocos2d/sprite-computer-graphics] For example, the Texas Instruments TMS9918 chip supports 32 sprites, but only four can appear on the same scan line.
[src:cocos2d/sprite-computer-graphics] The CPUs in modern computers, video game consoles, and mobile devices are fast enough that bitmaps can be drawn into a frame buffer without special hardware assistance.
[src:cocos2d/sprite-computer-graphics] Beyond that, GPUs can render vast numbers of scaled, rotated, anti-aliased, partially translucent, very high resolution images in parallel with the CPU.
[src:cocos2d/sprite-computer-graphics] According to Karl Guttag, one of two engineers for the 1979 Texas Instruments TMS9918 video display processor, this use of the word *sprite* came from David Ackley, a manager at TI.
[src:cocos2d/sprite-computer-graphics] It was also used by Danny Hillis at Texas Instruments in the late 1970s.
[src:cocos2d/sprite-computer-graphics] The term was derived from the fact that sprites "float" on top of the background image without overwriting it, much like a ghost or mythological sprite.
[src:cocos2d/sprite-computer-graphics] The use of sprites originated with arcade video games.
[src:cocos2d/sprite-computer-graphics] Nolan Bushnell came up with the original concept when he developed the first arcade video game, *Computer Space* (1971).
[src:cocos2d/sprite-computer-graphics] Technical limitations made it difficult to adapt the early mainframe game *Spacewar!* (1962), which performed an entire screen refresh for every little movement, so he came up with a solution to the problem: controlling each individual game element with a dedicated transistor.
[src:cocos2d/sprite-computer-graphics] The rockets were essentially hardwired bitmaps that moved around the screen independently of the background, an important innovation for producing screen images more efficiently and providing the basis for sprite graphics.
[src:cocos2d/sprite-computer-graphics] The earliest video games to represent player characters as human player sprites were arcade sports video games, beginning with Taito's *TV Basketball*, released in April 1974 and licensed to Midway Manufacturing for release in North America.
[src:cocos2d/sprite-computer-graphics] Designed by Tomohiro Nishikado, he wanted to move beyond simple *Pong*-style rectangles to character graphics, by rearranging the rectangle shapes into objects that look like basketball players and basketball hoops.
[src:cocos2d/sprite-computer-graphics] Ramtek released another sports video game in October 1974, *Baseball*, which similarly displayed human-like characters.
[src:cocos2d/sprite-computer-graphics] The Namco Galaxian arcade system board, for the 1979 arcade game *Galaxian*, displays animated, multi-colored sprites over a scrolling background.
[src:cocos2d/sprite-computer-graphics] It became the basis for Nintendo's *Radar Scope* and *Donkey Kong* arcade hardware and home consoles such as the Nintendo Entertainment System.
[src:cocos2d/sprite-computer-graphics] According to Steve Golson from General Computer Corporation, the term "stamp" was used instead of "sprite" at the time.
[src:cocos2d/sprite-computer-graphics] Signetics devised the first chips capable of generating sprite graphics (referred to as *objects* by Signetics) for home systems.
[src:cocos2d/sprite-computer-graphics] The Signetics 2636 video processors were first used in the 1978 1292 Advanced Programmable Video System and later in the 1979 Elektor TV Games Computer.
[src:cocos2d/sprite-computer-graphics] The Atari VCS, released in 1977, has a hardware sprite implementation where five graphical objects can be moved independently of the game playfield.
[src:cocos2d/sprite-computer-graphics] The term *sprite* was not in use at the time.
[src:cocos2d/sprite-computer-graphics] The VCS's sprites are called *movable objects* in the programming manual, further identified as two *players*, two *missiles*, and one *ball*.
[src:cocos2d/sprite-computer-graphics] These each consist of a single row of pixels that are displayed on a scan line.
[src:cocos2d/sprite-computer-graphics] To produce a two-dimensional shape, the sprite's single-row bitmap is altered by software from one scan line to the next.
[src:cocos2d/sprite-computer-graphics] The 1979 Atari 400 and 800 home computers have similar, but more elaborate, circuitry capable of moving eight single-color objects per scan line: four 8-bit wide *players* and four 2-bit wide *missiles*.
[src:cocos2d/sprite-computer-graphics] Each is the full height of the display—a long, thin strip.
[src:cocos2d/sprite-computer-graphics] DMA from a table in memory automatically sets the graphics pattern registers for each scan line.
[src:cocos2d/sprite-computer-graphics] Hardware registers control the horizontal position of each player and missile.
[src:cocos2d/sprite-computer-graphics] Vertical motion is achieved by moving the bitmap data within a player or missile's strip.
[src:cocos2d/sprite-computer-graphics] The feature was called *player/missile graphics* by Atari.
[src:cocos2d/sprite-computer-graphics] Texas Instruments developed the TMS9918 chip with sprite support for its 1979 TI-99/4 home computer.
[src:cocos2d/sprite-computer-graphics] An updated version is used in the 1981 TI-99/4A.
[src:cocos2d/sprite-computer-graphics] Sprites remained popular with the rise of 2.5D games (those which recreate a 3D game space from a 2D map) in the late 1980s and early 1990s.
[src:cocos2d/sprite-computer-graphics] A technique called billboarding allows 2.5D games to keep onscreen sprites rotated toward the player view at all times.
[src:cocos2d/sprite-computer-graphics] Some 2.5D games, such as 1993's *Doom*, allow the same entity to be represented by different sprites depending on its rotation relative to the viewer, furthering the illusion of 3D.
[src:cocos2d/sprite-computer-graphics] Fully 3D games usually present world objects as 3D models, but sprites are supported in some 3D game engines, such as GoldSrc and Unreal, and may be billboarded or locked to fixed orientations.
[src:cocos2d/sprite-computer-graphics] Sprites remain useful for small details, particle effects, and other applications where the lack of a third dimension is not a major detriment.
[src:cocos2d/sprite-computer-graphics] These are base hardware specs and do not include additional programming techniques, such as using raster interrupts to repurpose sprites mid-frame.
